<p><i><b>Network</b></i> is a <a href="/wiki/1976_in_film" title="1976 in film">1976</a> <a href="/wiki/Satire" title="Satire">satirical film</a> about a fictional <a href="/wiki/Television_network" title="Television network">television network</a>, <a href="/wiki/Union_Broadcasting_System" title="Union Broadcasting System">Union Broadcasting System</a> (UBS), and its struggle with poor <a href="/wiki/Nielsen_Ratings" title="Nielsen Ratings">ratings</a>. It was written by <a href="/wiki/Paddy_Chayefsky" title="Paddy Chayefsky">Paddy Chayefsky</a> and directed by <a href="/wiki/Sidney_Lumet" title="Sidney Lumet">Sidney Lumet</a>, and stars <a href="/wiki/Faye_Dunaway" title="Faye Dunaway">Faye Dunaway</a>, <a href="/wiki/William_Holden" title="William Holden">William Holden</a>, <a href="/wiki/Peter_Finch" title="Peter Finch">Peter Finch</a> and <a href="/wiki/Robert_Duvall" title="Robert Duvall">Robert Duvall</a> and features <a href="/wiki/Wesley_Addy" title="Wesley Addy">Wesley Addy</a>, <a href="/wiki/Ned_Beatty" title="Ned Beatty">Ned Beatty</a> and <a href="/wiki/Beatrice_Straight" title="Beatrice Straight">Beatrice Straight</a>. The film won four <a href="/wiki/Academy_Awards" title="Academy Awards" class="mw-redirect">Academy Awards</a>, including <a href="/wiki/Academy_Award_for_Best_Actor" title="Academy Award for Best Actor">Best Actor</a>, <a href="/wiki/Academy_Award_for_Best_Actress" title="Academy Award for Best Actress">Best Actress</a>, <a href="/wiki/Academy_Award_for_Best_Supporting_Actress" title="Academy Award for Best Supporting Actress">Best Supporting Actress</a> and <a href="/wiki/Academy_Award_for_Writing_(Original_Screenplay)" title="Academy Award for Writing (Original Screenplay)" class="mw-redirect">Best Writing, Screenplay Written Directly for the Screen</a>.</p>
<p><i>Network</i> has continued to receive recognition, decades after its initial release. In 2000, the film was selected for preservation in the United States <a href="/wiki/National_Film_Registry" title="National Film Registry">National Film Registry</a> by the <a href="/wiki/Library_of_Congress" title="Library of Congress">Library of Congress</a> as being "culturally, historically, or aesthetically significant". <a href="/wiki/Producers_Guild_of_America_Awards_2001" title="Producers Guild of America Awards 2001">In 2002</a>, it was inducted into the <a href="/wiki/Producers_Guild_of_America" title="Producers Guild of America">Producers Guild of America</a> Hall of Fame as a film that has "set an enduring standard for American entertainment."<sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> In 2006, Chayefsky's script was voted one of the top ten movie scripts of all-time by the <a href="/wiki/Writers_Guild_of_America,_East" title="Writers Guild of America, East">Writers Guild of America, East</a>. In 2007, the film was 64th among the <a href="/wiki/AFI%27s_100_Years..._100_Movies_(10th_Anniversary_Edition)" title="AFI's 100 Years... 100 Movies (10th Anniversary Edition)">Top 100 Greatest American Films</a> as chosen by the <a href="/wiki/American_Film_Institute" title="American Film Institute">American Film Institute</a>, a ranking slightly higher than the one AFI gave it <a href="/wiki/AFI%27s_100_Years..._100_Movies#1998_List" title="AFI's 100 Years... 100 Movies">ten years earlier</a>.</p>
